Steven Swiniarski wrote:
>============================================================
>The Agora FAQ v0.2 Beta
>============================================================
>
>3.0: Democracy in Agora.
>  3.1: How do I vote?

As of Jan. 1998, all voting on Proposals, Elections and Referenda
must be done in public, ie by sending a message to the Public Forum
during the Voting Period. The message should specify what you're voting
on, and how you are voting.
[cf. 1764]

>   +3.1.2: Voting Token, what's that?

Voting Tokens are a Currency, the primary use of which is to vote on
Proposals. Each vote you cast on a Proposal costs you one Voting
Token, which you will be billed by the Assessor after the end of the
Voting Period. [This assumes that P3693 will pass.]
[cf. 1442]

>   +3.1.3: This is a democracy, but voting isn't free?

The best things in life may be free, but the best things in Agora
are not. Or at least, they aren't any more. For about the first
two years of the game, until March 1995, voting was completely
free. For about two years after that, Players' first votes were
free, and Players had the option to cast a second vote, at the
expense of a Voting Token, which at the time were called Extra
Votes. A desire to make Extra Votes more valuable led to the
removal of the right to cast a free first vote, in April 1997,
at which time Extra Votes were renamed Voting Tokens.
[cf. 1442, especially the History]

>   +3.1.4: Then what's Presence?  Isn't that a vote?

Technically, no, Presence is not a vote. It doesn't cost you
a Voting Token to declare your Presence on a Proposal. 
Declaring Presence is just like abstaining on a Proposal,
while counting towards Quorum. Since the cheapest way to get
a Proposal to fail is to get it to fail Quorum, declaring
Presence has the effect of expressing very mild support for
a Proposal; mild opposition would be expressed by not voting
or declaring Presence on it at all.
[cf. 1715]

>   +3.1.5: How do I get a Voting Token then?

This is always a major focus of legislative activity, so any answer
given here is unlikely to remain up to date for long. At time of
writing, the most common way of earning VTs is to hold one of the
Offices which pays a weekly Salary [cf. 1007]. Making a Proposal
which gets adopted will earn you 2 VTs [cf. 833]. Judges also earn
a salary for delivering Judgement [cf. 591].

>   +3.1.6: I can't vote on anything without a Voting Token?

[Once again, assuming P3693 passes.]
It's not quite that simple. First of all, voting on Referenda and
in Elections remains completely free. Secondly, it is possible to
vote on Proposals without Voting Tokens. However, you will then
have to find a way to pay the Voting Token bills that voting on
Proposals will cause you to incur. If you cannot do so, the 
penalties may be severe.
[cf. 1442, 1713]



