What do people think about this?  In an election like the forthcoming
one for Justiciar there are five candidates, and assuming that all of
them attract some support, there will be a large number of wasted
votes.

A standard fix for this sort of problem is to use a preferential
voting system where Voters rank the Candidates in order of preference,
and then if after the all the first choice votes have been tallied
no-one has a majority, the candidate with the least number of votes is
dropped and all of their votes are redistributed to second choice
candidates.  &c &c.  I understand that this is how Australian
elections to their lower hourse work.

However, for all that this might give us a more rational system (and
beware: what do you do if A gets five votes and B and C both get 3?),
it will also make voting in Elections less strategically interesting.
At a national level, where these things are (perhaps :-) more
important, I'd be the first to campaign for a more rational system
(having to vote strategically (i.e. counter-intuitively) to get a
desired result seems a pretty good indication that a system needs
reform), but perhaps this sort of thing makes Agora more interesting. 

Michael.

PS: preference voting as practised in Australia does not produce
proportional results on a party basis in the legislature, which is
probably why the big parties in the UK are so keen on it as a possible
reform of the existing system.  For proportionality you need
multi-member constituencies and the Single Transferable Vote system
(as in the Republic of Ireland), or you need a system that allows
people to vote for parties directly and which then adjusts the
legislature appropriately, as happens (with variations) in Germany,
Israel and New Zealand.

