believe that the current elections are the first time I've really seen
the group structure used for something like party politics. For
example, if the Threat (four votes) all vote for Scott, and maybe buy
a few more votes, the only way for Scott to lose would be a
considerable degree of planning by all the other players, so they
don't split their votes and let Scott win.

This can be fun, and while I'd rather not see an all-Threat
government, I'd rather have some fun with these elections than a more
complicated election system that avoids these "problems".

