Hi all,

Just an attempt to spice up the upcoming elections: here are some data
on Offices held, and incomes connected to these offices, sorted by
groups. 

Before the current elections, the situation looked like this (I'm
leaving out the paper tiger office of CinC, because it doesn't really
play any role at the moment and doesn't draw a salary, either).

Group      no of offices     sum of salaries

Threat      7 of 15 (47%)      9 VTs of 21 (43%)

Order       3 of 15 (20%)    4.5 VTs of 21 (21%)

X group     2 of 15 (13%)    2.5 VTs of 21 (12%)

none        3 of 15 (20%)      5 VTs of 21 (24%)


In the current elections most players have already cast their votes;
the only votes I have not seen yet are by three unaffiliated players
and one member of the Threat (elJefe). At the moment the elections for
CotC, Notary, Promotor and Wizard are close contests between members
of the Threat and the Order - exactly split votes at the moment, and I
guess elJefe's vote will help the Threat win them all... For
Scorekeepor Harlequin might win, because Swann attracted some votes,
including one from a member of the Threat. Morale: If the Threat votes
unanimously, they can win elections.

The same goes for the Justiciar election, which just began (the
non-Threat votes will be split among many other candidates), while the
elections for Archivist and Chancellor are between Threat members and
unaffiliated candidates. So the Threat can win these, too. Then we
have: 


Group      no of offices     sum of salaries

Threat      9 of 15 (60%)   11.5 VTs of 21 (55%)

Order       3 of 15 (20%)      5 VTs of 21 (24%)

X group     2 of 15 (13%)    2.5 VTs of 21 (12%)

none        1 of 15 (20%)      2 VTs of 21 ( 9%)


Bad times for independent candidates, good times for the
Threat... I wonder whether the last revolution really was but a lame
attempt to use the delegation loophole in the revolution
rules. Especially as offices are gaining more and more real political
