Charles E. Carroll wrote:
>
>Michael Norrish wrote:
>>
>>What do people think about this?  In an election like the forthcoming
>>one for Justiciar there are five candidates, and assuming that all of
>>them attract some support, there will be a large number of wasted
>>votes.
>
>I think it's less likely with Public Voting.
>
>Consider the following: last year, the School of Library and
>Information Studies (SLIS) here at the University of Wisconsin-
>Madison decided to produce a T-shirt to sell to students in the
>school.  There were about ten candidate slogans for the
>T-shirt, and students were asked to vote for one.  However,
>voting was essentially public: a sheet was posted with the
>possible slogans, and students were asked to place a check
>mark by the one preferred (we were on our honor to vote
>only once).
>
>Only two of the slogans got any votes at all.
>
>I don't think it's because everyone wanted only one of these
>two slogans.  Rather, it was obvious early in the voting
>that one of these two would win, and so people chose
>to cast their votes in a meaningful manner, for one of
>those two.  (I don't remember what the slogans were, so
>don't ask.)
>
>I think such a system would be further enhanced if we
>allowed people to change their votes during voting.
>(Why isn't changing votes allowed during Referenda/Elections,
>anyway?  This never made sense to me.)

That's an interesting anecdote, Chuck. To me it demonstrates that
the current system magnifies random effects due to early voting.
If it had happened that supporters of some of the other slogans had
voted earlier, it may well have been two completely different
slogans that ended up getting all the votes.

In that light, it's interesting to think about the effect that
indelible voting has. It certainly makes an enormous difference to
the political process, just as public voting does. Once you've voted,
you've thrown all your negotiating power out the window. On the other
hand, early voting can be strategically crucial in persuading other
undecided voters that the candidate you support has a chance of
winning and that therefore their votes will not be wasted if they
also support your preferred candidate. Of course, the thing to do in
that case is announce your support for a certain candidate early on,
but withhold your vote until you have a clearer picture of what
others are going to do.

Moving to a system like the Proposal system where votes can be
changed would certainly be quite different. Negotiating about votes
would go on until the last minute, since someone might renege on
a deal they made with you if the price is right. Indelible voting
provides a public way of keeping one's promises.

Now, as between these two system, I don't have a strong preference.
They're both interesting in their own ways. But I do think it's
kind of neat that we're using one system for Proposals and the
other for Elections and Referenda (with the additional difference
of course that voting in Elections and Referenda is free). This
way, we get to explore both kinds of voting system at once!
