in the game, and I think that's reflected in the public interest in
them. 12 of 16 Players have already voted, and there's a good chance
that by the end of the Voting Periods, we will have seen every single
Player cast a vote, something which I do not believe has ever
happened before in the nearly three years we've been conducting
Elections for Offices. At least three Players have been keeping
personal tallies of the votes cast so far, and that information
is being disseminated and discussed by the Players. Pretty clearly,
Players are pursuing private strategies and negotiations. These are
very healthy signs that the game is really alive and holding the
interest of the Players. It's a good time to be playing Agora, and
I think we all know why: VT scarcity has made holding Office more
desirable than it ever has been before, and public voting has enabled
everyone to see how an Election is progressing while it is occurring,
which make the contests more interesting. It's nice to see that,
at least once in a while, policy can work out the way you hoped.


